```cpp
#include <iostream>

using namespace std;

int fibonacci(int n) {
    if (n <= 1)
        return n;
    else
        return fibonacci(n-1) + fibonacci(n-2);
}

int main() {
    int n;
    cout << "Enter the value of n: ";
    cin >> n;
    cout << "The " << n << "th Fibonacci number is: " << fibonacci(n);
    return 0;
}
```

This program works by recursively calling the `fibonacci` function with the input `n` until it reaches the base case where `n` is less than or equal to 1. At this point, it returns `n`. Otherwise, it calculates the Fibonacci number by adding the result of the recursive call with `n-1` and `n-2`.

Please note that this program uses recursion, which can lead to stack overflow for large values of `n` due to the excessive number of function calls. For large values of `n`, it is more efficient to use an iterative approach or to use a memoization technique to store the results of previous calculations.

